  <p>This guide explains how to calculate your personal daily water needs and how factors like body weight, activity, and climate affect your requirements.</p>

  <h2 id="the-8-glasses-a-day-rule-is-it-accurate">The "8 Glasses a Day" Rule — Is It Accurate?</h2>
  <p>The popular recommendation of eight 250ml glasses (2 litres) per day is a convenient guideline but not a universal truth. It originated from a 1945 US dietary recommendation that was later taken out of context. The actual amount varies significantly based on individual factors.</p>
  <p>A more reliable approach is to base your intake on your body weight, activity level, and the climate you live in.</p>

  <div class="callout"><p><strong>Simple baseline:</strong> A common evidence-based starting point is approximately 35ml of water per kilogram of body weight per day. For a 70kg adult, that is 2.45 litres — close to the 8-glasses guideline, but adjusted for your actual body size.</p></div>


