<h2 id="how-body-weight-affects-water-needs">How Body Weight Affects Water Needs</h2>
  <p>Larger bodies require more water to maintain cellular function, regulate temperature, and support organ health. This is why a 50kg person and a 100kg person have very different hydration requirements, even if they live in the same climate and have the same activity level.</p>

  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Body Weight</th><th>Base Daily Water Need</th><th>In Glasses (250ml)</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>50 kg</td><td>1.75 L</td><td>~7 glasses</td></tr>
      <tr><td>60 kg</td><td>2.10 L</td><td>~8 glasses</td></tr>
      <tr><td>70 kg</td><td>2.45 L</td><td>~10 glasses</td></tr>
      <tr><td>80 kg</td><td>2.80 L</td><td>~11 glasses</td></tr>
      <tr><td>90 kg</td><td>3.15 L</td><td>~13 glasses</td></tr>
      <tr><td>100 kg</td><td>3.50 L</td><td>~14 glasses</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="how-climate-affects-hydration-especially-in-the-tropics">How Climate Affects Hydration — Especially in the Tropics</h2>
  <p>People living in hot, humid climates like Malaysia, Singapore, Indonesia, and Thailand have significantly higher water needs than those in cooler climates. Sweating is the body's primary cooling mechanism, and in a tropical climate, you can lose 0.5–1 litre of fluid per hour during moderate outdoor activity.</p>
  <p>For people in tropical climates, adding 0.5–1 litre to your base daily intake is a reasonable adjustment, particularly if you spend time outdoors or in non-air-conditioned environments.</p>

  <h2 id="how-exercise-increases-water-requirements">How Exercise Increases Water Requirements</h2>
  <p>Physical activity dramatically increases fluid loss through sweat and respiration. A moderately intense 60-minute workout can result in 0.5–2 litres of sweat loss, depending on body size, intensity, and environmental temperature.</p>
  <p>A practical rule of thumb: drink an additional 500ml of water for every 30–45 minutes of moderate exercise. For intense or prolonged sessions, consider a drink with electrolytes to replace sodium and potassium lost through sweat.</p>

  <h2 id="how-to-tell-if-you-are-drinking-enough">How to Tell If You Are Drinking Enough</h2>
  <p>The simplest and most reliable indicator of hydration is the colour of your urine.</p>

