  <p>Other signs of dehydration include dry mouth, headache, fatigue, difficulty concentrating, and reduced urine frequency. Many people misinterpret mild dehydration as hunger, which can lead to unnecessary snacking.</p>

  <h2 id="practical-tips-to-drink-more-water">Practical Tips to Drink More Water</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start every morning with a glass of water</strong> before coffee or tea — it rehydrates you after 7–8 hours without fluids.</li>
    <li><strong>Carry a reusable water bottle</strong> and set a target based on your bottle size (e.g. finish three 700ml bottles throughout the day).</li>
    <li><strong>Set hourly reminders</strong> on your phone until drinking regularly becomes a habit.</li>
    <li><strong>Eat water-rich foods</strong> — cucumber, watermelon, strawberries, and leafy greens all contribute meaningfully to daily fluid intake.</li>
    <li><strong>Drink a glass of water before each meal</strong> — this also slightly reduces calorie intake at mealtimes.</li>
    <li><strong>Flavour your water</strong> with sliced lemon, cucumber, or mint if plain water feels unappealing.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="does-coffee-and-tea-count">Does Coffee and Tea Count?</h2>
  <p>Yes — to a meaningful degree. Despite caffeine's mild diuretic effect, research consistently shows that moderate consumption of coffee and tea still results in a net positive contribution to daily fluid intake. You do not need to subtract your morning coffee from your water target.</p>
  <p>Alcohol, however, is a genuine diuretic and leads to increased fluid loss. For every alcoholic drink, consuming an additional glass of water helps offset the dehydrating effect.</p>

  <h2 id="can-you-drink-too-much-water">Can You Drink Too Much Water?</h2>
  <p>In healthy adults with normal kidney function, it is very difficult to drink too much water under normal circumstances. The kidneys can process roughly 0.8–1 litre per hour. Hyponatraemia (dangerously low blood sodium from excess water) is almost exclusively seen in endurance athletes who drink large amounts without adequate electrolyte replacement over several hours.</p>
  <p>For everyday purposes, drinking to thirst and monitoring urine colour is a perfectly safe and effective strategy.</p>

<div class="faq-section">
  <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much water should I drink per day?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">General guidance is 2.0–2.5 litres (8–10 cups) per day for adults in temperate climates. In hot climates like Malaysia and Singapore, needs increase to 3–4 litres due to higher sweat losses. Individual needs vary with body size, activity level, and diet — people who eat water-rich foods (fruits and vegetables) need slightly less from drinks.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does coffee and tea count towards daily water intake?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Yes — despite their mild diuretic effect, caffeinated beverages like coffee and tea provide a net positive contribution to daily fluid intake. The small diuretic effect does not cancel out the water they provide. Plain water remains the best choice for hydration, but coffee, tea, and other beverages count.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is it possible to drink too much water?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Yes — hyponatraemia (dangerously low blood sodium from over-dilution) can occur from drinking excessive water rapidly, particularly during endurance events. For everyday life, the kidneys can process about 0.8–1 litre per hour, so drinking within this rate is safe. Urine colour is the most practical gauge of appropriate hydration.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why do I feel thirsty even when I drink a lot of water?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Persistent thirst despite adequate fluid intake can be a sign of diabetes (high blood sugar draws water out of cells), diabetes insipidus (impaired water regulation by the kidneys), or certain medications. If you are consistently thirsty despite drinking 2–3 litres daily, a GP check is warranted.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does drinking more water speed up metabolism?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Slightly — drinking 500ml of cold water increases metabolic rate by about 30% for 30–40 minutes, burning approximately 24 kcal per litre of cold water. This metabolic effect is real but small. Water's more significant contribution to weight management is through replacing high-calorie drinks and reducing appetite before meals.</div>
  </div>
